Electrochemical behavior of some analytes and subsequently the shape and peak current of the obtained voltammograms are controlled by the nature analytes and pH value of the supporting electrolyte. For this purpose, the effect of pH, on the electrooxidation of IMB at the CuFe2O4/ZIF-8@GQDs/GCE was studied by linear sweep voltammetric technique in 0.1 M PBS containing 30 μM IMB with different pH values in the range of 3.0 to 10.0 at the scan rate of 100 mV s−1 (Fig. 6
                        ). The outputs illustrated that the pH value affects both the peak current and potential of the LSV grams of IMB. As can be seen in Fig. 6 B, the anodic current peak increased with the pH change from 3.0 to 6.0 and then decreased in pH from pH 7.0 to 10.0. Also, the oxidation peak of IMB shifts to a negative potential with increasing pH under a regression equation of Epa(V) = −0.0339 pH +1.0797 (R2 = 0.993). The peak potential diagram in terms of pH can be seen in Fig. 6B. As shown in the equation, the slope of the peak potential changes is obtained as a function of the pH of the solution equal to 0.0339 V pH −1, which is close to the slope of the Nernst Eq. [65]. Therefore, we can deduce that the number of two electrons and one proton involved in the reaction are equal [62,63,66]. Based on the obtained results and according to the literature reported for IMB electrooxidation [21,62,63,66,67], the oxidation mechanism of IMB can be expressed as in Scheme 2
                        , in which the participation of two electrons and one proton in the redox reaction. From the chemical point, IMB has different pKa values (pKa1 = 2.5, pKa2 = 4.0, and pKa3 = 8.2) and the drug is positively charged at pH 7.0 [9,21,62,63,66–68]. Based on the value of pKa for IMB molecules, at a solution pH lower than pKa, due to the protonation of IMB molecules, its oxidation process may be more difficult and therefore the current should increase with increasing pH around its pKa. According to the pKa values of IMB, this drug has a positive charge in solution at pH 7.0 and a negative charge at pH > 8.2. Perhaps, the surface of the modifier becomes negatively polarized with respect to pHpzc and the electrostatic interaction between the negatively charged nanocomposite and the positively charged IMB is responsible for the obtained maximum oxidation current.

Due to various advantages such as higher faradic current, lower background current and better sensitivity, the differential pulse voltammetry (DPV) technique was used to quantitate determination of the IMB concentration at the proposed modified electrode: CuFe2O4/ZIF-8@GQDs/GCE. To achieve the newly designed sensor working range and deeply investigating the electroanalytical performance of the CuFe2O4/ZIF-8@GQDs/GCE, the corresponding DPV profiles at different concentrations of IMB were recorded at the optimized measuring conditions (0.1 M PBS at pH = 7.0 and accumulation time of 60 s) (Fig. 9
                        ). It was clearly observed that the peak current increases proportionally with the increase in drug concentration. The calibration graph (the relationship between the changes in the peak current of the plotted voltammograms and the concentration of IMB in the range of 0.02–11.85 μM and 11.85–94.2 μM, according to the equation given below) is presented in Fig. 9B. Based on the calculations and confirmatory experiments, the calculated limit of detection (LOD) and limit of quantitation (LOQ) (LOD = 3S/m and LOQ = 10S/m, where S denoted the sensitivity Factor and m is slope of the calibration curve) [70] are 1.2 nM and 4.1 nM respectively, suggesting that the proposed sensor can detect ultralow concentrations of IMB. In summary, the comparison of the results obtained from the newly designed sensor with other IMB electrochemical sensors reported shows that the strategy applied in this study in terms of detection limit and dynamic range is well comparable with previous reports or compared to some better than the methods provided (as clearly shown in Table 1
                        ). As can be seen the designed sensor has several advantages such as cost-effectiveness, admirable modification, easy accessibility and low background current compared to other electrodes. Therefore, the results show the high and acceptable performance of this sensor for the determination of IMB by the DPV method.
